         <abstract>
            <p> A la veille de la commémoration religieuse, civile et savante de la révocation de l'Edit de Nantes, quelle est la situation du protestantisme français? Inquiétante ou prometteuse, c'est selon, nous dit Jean Baubérot. Ce groupe carrefour, qui a tant fait pour imposer le pluralisme culturel et démocratique en France, semble n'avoir plus d'autre stratégie qu'un œcuménisme déçu, d'autre logique que la déstructuration de ses communautés. Et pourtant, d'évangélismes en ferveurs tziganes, l'Esprit souffle encore. Timides et provocants, voici, trois siècles après, les fils du Désert et du Refuge. /// The Fall of 1985 will see the commemoration of the revocation of the Edict of Nantes. The author takes this occasion to describe the situation of French Protestantism. In the 19th century, the Protestants had accepted as inevitable the secularization of post-1789 society, and they were instrumental in making it come about. In the 20th century, they adopted an oecumenical strategy, with the Vatican Council II coming as a "divine surprise". Today, they are hesitating between a timid withdrawal and a new evangelical offensive, particularly important in these times of religious disaffection. Three centuries have gone by since the Revocation, but the memory of it is still a help for innovation and a test of vitality for this minority to which the cultural and democratic pluralism of France is so beholden. </p>
